gov.usgs.comcat

Class ComCatEvent

  • java.lang.Object
    • gov.usgs.comcat.ComCatEvent

  • public final class ComCatEvent
extends java.lang.Object
    This class returns QuakeML from the earthquake.usgs.gov website given an event ID from comcat using the 'query' command (https://earthquake.usgs.gov/fdsnws/event/1/query?[PARAMETERS]. The user only needs to supply up to the /event/1/query as its base URL. It supports most of the query options as well. Seed the documentation of the query format at https://earthquake.usgs.gov/fdsnws/event/1. Normal Usage : 
     1) create the ComCatEvent object and optionally set the base URL to something like "https://earthquake.usgs.gov/fdsnws/"
 2) Optionally use setParams() to set the eventID,
 3) Optionally :
 a) use setLatLongLimit() to pick a geographic region
 b) us setLatLongRadius() to set a circular retions
 c) use setStartEndTime() to set the start and end time
 d) use setMaxDepth(), setMinDepth(), use setMaxMagnitude(), or setMinMagnitude() to limit the set.
 e) use setFormat() if something other than quakeml format is needed.
 f) Other options are setIncludeAllMagnitudes(), setIncludeAllOrigins(), setIncludeArrivals(), setIncludeDeletedEvents()
 setIncludeSuperseded(), setCatalog(), setContributor()
 4) Call executeURL() to fetch the data from the FDSN server, this will return the length of the returned document
 5) call parseQuakeML() to marshal/parse the QuakeML document returned, this will return the number of events in the document
 6) For simple parsing, call getEvent(int n) for each event starting with zero and process the events using the getter functions
 7) call clearURL() to start over and setup  to start a new request
    There are advanced usage methods to get the full QuakeML object or the preferred origin as a JAXB object, or to get the full text of the QuakeML document.
    Picks can be obtained by NSCL by calling "getPick(NSCl)" or an ArrayList of Simple picks is available from getPicksList(); The other getter methods return preferred magnitudes, origin information parse out from the document. Since there are many origins and magnitudes only the preferred ones are picked apart. To process all of the origins or magnitudes get the origin or magnitudes list as JAXB objects from the

      • setParams

        public final void setParams(java.lang.String format,
                            long start,
                            long endtime,
                            double lat,
                            double lng,
                            double radiuskm,
                            double minMag,
                            double maxMag)
        This is a convenience methods for the most common kind of querys from the Edge/CWB picking system.
        Parameters:
        format - Set the document return type, normally this is null and "xml" is the format
        start - Set the start time for querying events (if <=0 , then do not use a time range)
        endtime - Set the end time for querying events
        lat - latitude combined with lng and radius to create a geographic restraint
        lng - longitude for circle restraint
        radiuskm - Radius in kilometers for circle restarting
        minMag - If > 0., then set a minimum magnitude
        maxMag - if > 0., then set a maximum magnitude

      • getEvent

        public Event getEvent(int nevent)
        Get the nth event from the document and this event is returned as a JAXB event object. You can use the returne object to get to all of the JAXB representation of the object. JAXB uses a lot of lists based on the QuakeML xsd definitions. You can see in this code how the preferred information is picked out from the list of origins, mags, etc and how to process the picks.
        Parameters:
        nevent - THe event number from zero to the number of events
        Returns:
        The event object just positioned.
